If systems A & B are in thermal equilibrium, and systems B & C are in thermal equilibrium then systems A & C are also in thermal equilibrium.
Both heat and work are ways for the internal energy of a system to change, and the energy of a system is conserved when the net heat and work acting on that system is zero.
No heat engine can convert all of its supplied input heat into an equal amount of output work.
If the net external force acting on a system is zero, then the momentum of that system doesn't change.
The total mass of the universe cannot change.
The total energy of the universe cannot change.
Any object in motion will stay in motion, and any object at rest will remain at rest unless acted on by an external force.
